{"id":"1207.0109","submitter":"Rob Schneiderman","authors":"James Conant, Rob Schneiderman, and Peter Teichner","title":"Universal quadratic forms and Whitney tower intersection invariants","comments":"This paper subsumes the second half (Section 7) of the previously\n  posted paper \"Universal Quadratic Forms and Untwisting Whitney Towers\"\n  (http://arxiv.org/abs/1101.3480)","journal-ref":"GTM 18 (2012) 35-60","doi":"10.2140/gtm.2012.18.35","report-no":null,"categories":"math.GT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The first part of this paper exposits a simple geometric description of the\nKirby-Siebenmann invariant of a 4--manifold in terms of a quadratic refinement\nof its intersection form. This is the first in a sequence of higher-order\nintersection invariants of Whitney towers studied by the authors, particularly\nfor the 4--ball.\n  In the second part of this paper, a general theory of quadratic forms is\ndeveloped and then specialized from the non-commutative to the commutative to\nfinally, the symmetric settings. The intersection invariant for twisted Whitney\ntowers is shown to be the universal symmetric refinement of the framed\nintersection invariant. As a corollary we obtain a short exact sequence that\nhas been essential in the understanding of Whitney towers in the 4--ball.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 30 Jun 2012 15:18:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-20"}
{"id":"1207.0110","submitter":"Elisabeth Bouchaud","authors":"Baudouin Saintyves and Olivier Dauchot and Elisabeth Bouchaud","title":"Bulk elastic fingering instability in Hele-Shaw cells","comments":"Submitted to Physical Review letters; 5 pages; 6 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 111, 047801 (2013)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.111.047801","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.soft","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We demonstrate experimentally the existence of a purely elastic fingering\ninstability which arises when air penetrates into an elastomer confined in a\nHele-Shaw cell. Fingers appear sequentially and propagate within the bulk of\nthe material as soon as a critical strain, independent of the elastic modulus,\nis exceeded. Their width depends non-linearly on the distance between the\nconfining glass plates. A key element in the driving force of the instability\nis the adhesion of layers of gels to the plates, which results in a\nconsiderable expense of elastic energy during the growth of the air bubble.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 30 Jun 2012 15:28:21 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 17 Aug 2013 14:56:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-01-19"}
